ld it be ok?

It would be ok, but we don't need that. It should be sufficient for us to build with the minimum rdma-core version we want to support and leaving without an upper cap. So one approach we could take is whenever there's a new major UCX release we build it with the latest `rdma-core` and leave it without an upper cap. E.g., say `rdma-core=50.0` is the latest release when `ucx=1.16.0` comes out, we could simply build `ucx=1.16.x` (1.16 with all its minor releases) build in conda-forge with `rdma-core=50.0` but leave the runtime pin uncapped to `rdma-core>=50.0`, and that should suffice supporting new versions.","reactions":{"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/conda-forge/ucx-split-feedstock/issues/comments/1754543835/reactions","total_count":0,"+1":0,"-1":0,"laugh":0,"hooray":0,"confused":0,"heart":0,"rocket":0,"eyes":0},"performed_via_github_app":null}}

